Ziyi Li (ziyi.li@emory.edu)

1. Tidyr package:

The package tidyr

  • written by Hadley Wickham.
  • addresses the common problem of wanting to reshape your data for plotting and use by different R functions.
  • Sometimes we want data sets where we have one row per measurement. Sometimes we want a data frame where each measurement type has its own column, and rows are instead more aggregated groups. Moving back and forth between these formats is nontrivial.
  • tidyr gives you tools for this and more sophisticated data manipulation.

Three main functions in tidyr:

  • separate()
  • unite()
  • gather()
  • spread()

1.1 Install and load package

# install.packages("tidyr")

library("tidyr")

1.2 separate() can split a function into two (or more) columns.

musicians <- data.frame(FirstName = c("Frederic", "Wolfgang", "Ludwig"),
                        LastName = c("Chopin", "Mozart", "Beethoven"),
                        YearBorn = c(1810, 1756, 1770),
                        YearDeath = c(1849, 1791, 1827),
                        BornPlace = c("Zelezowa, Poland", "Salzburg, Austria", "Mechelen, German"))
musicians
##   FirstName  LastName YearBorn YearDeath         BornPlace
## 1  Frederic    Chopin     1810      1849  Zelezowa, Poland
## 2  Wolfgang    Mozart     1756      1791 Salzburg, Austria
## 3    Ludwig Beethoven     1770      1827  Mechelen, German
# separete(dataset_name, variables_to_separate, names_of_new_columns, separator)
separate(musicians, BornPlace, c("City", "Country"), sep=",")
##   FirstName  LastName YearBorn YearDeath     City  Country
## 1  Frederic    Chopin     1810      1849 Zelezowa   Poland
## 2  Wolfgang    Mozart     1756      1791 Salzburg  Austria
## 3    Ludwig Beethoven     1770      1827 Mechelen   German

1.3 unite() can merge two columns into two.

#unite(dataset_name, new_column_name, columns_to_unite, separator)
unite(musicians, "FullName", c(FirstName, LastName), sep=" ")
##           FullName YearBorn YearDeath         BornPlace
## 1  Frederic Chopin     1810      1849  Zelezowa, Poland
## 2  Wolfgang Mozart     1756      1791 Salzburg, Austria
## 3 Ludwig Beethoven     1770      1827  Mechelen, German

1.4 gather() can transform data from wide-format to long-format.

Ref.

worknum <- data.frame(Name = c("Chopin", "Mozart", "Beethoven"),
                        Etude = c(103, 80, 46),
                        Waltz = c(36, 12, 54),
                        Symphony = c(24, 41, 55))

worknum
##        Name Etude Waltz Symphony
## 1    Chopin   103    36       24
## 2    Mozart    80    12       41
## 3 Beethoven    46    54       55
# gather(dataset_name, new_variable_name1, new_variable_name2, variables_to_stack)
worknum2 <- gather(worknum, work_type, num_work, Etude:Symphony)
worknum2
##        Name work_type num_work
## 1    Chopin     Etude      103
## 2    Mozart     Etude       80
## 3 Beethoven     Etude       46
## 4    Chopin     Waltz       36
## 5    Mozart     Waltz       12
## 6 Beethoven     Waltz       54
## 7    Chopin  Symphony       24
## 8    Mozart  Symphony       41
## 9 Beethoven  Symphony       55

1.5 spread() can transform data from long-format to wide-format.

#spread(dataset_name, column_to_be_spread, values_that_multiple_columns_take)
spread(worknum2, work_type, num_work)
##        Name Etude Symphony Waltz
## 1 Beethoven    46       55    54
## 2    Chopin   103       24    36
## 3    Mozart    80       41    12

2. Readr package:

The package readr

  • written by Hadley Wickham.
  • the commonly used read.table() and read.csv() functions are provided by the basic function Utils.
  • Compared to the Utils package, readr is multiple times faster, very easy to use and have consistent names.

<reference: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=opai4Wmp6Zo&t=172s.>

2.1 Install and load readr package.

# install.packages("readr")
library(readr)

2.2 Quick start: read_delim()

The core function in readr is read_delim(), which have similar functions to read.csv(). Example: read in a NBA player data csv file,

file_location <- "https://www.dropbox.com/s/ialbx8rgvqnofif/player_data.csv?dl=1"
out1 <- read_delim(file_location, delim=",")
head(out1)
## # A tibble: 6 x 8

Specify column type by col_types. If not specify column types, read_delim will guess the type of each column by the first 30 observations.

out6 <- read_delim(file_location, delim=",", col_types = "cddc____")
head(out6)

Select observations to read in by skip and n_max:

head(out1)
## # A tibble: 6 x 8
##   name    year_start year_end position height weight birth_date college    
##   <chr>        <dbl>    <dbl> <chr>    <chr>   <dbl> <chr>      <chr>      
## 1 Alaa A…       1991     1995 F-C      10-Jun    240 24-Jun-68  Duke Unive…
## 2 Zaid A…       1969     1978 C-F      9-Jun     235 7-Apr-46   Iowa State…
## 3 Kareem…       1970     1989 C        2-Jul     225 16-Apr-47  University…

## 5 Tariq …       1998     2003 F        6-Jun     223 3-Nov-74   San Jose S…
## 6 Sharee…       1997     2008 F        9-Jun     225 11-Dec-76  University…
## skip the first two rows, read in up to 3 rows
out7 <- read_delim(file_location, delim=",", skip = 2, n_max = 3)
head(out7)
## # A tibble: 3 x 8
##   `Zaid Abdul-Azi… `1969` `1978` `C-F` `9-Jun` `235` `7-Apr-46`
